42:33.588 --> 42:36.154
It might be your proud
Southern history, C.P.,

42:36.156 --> 42:37.987
but it sure as hell
ain't ours.

42:37.989 --> 42:38.989
All right.

42:39.789 --> 42:41.854
Integrated schools have
"blacks only" assemblies,

42:41.856 --> 42:44.387
"blacks only"
Martin Luther King this, that.

42:44.389 --> 42:45.653
That ain't my history.

42:45.655 --> 42:47.121
You wanna talk about schools?

42:47.123 --> 42:49.222
Let's talk about schools,
Mr. Riddick.

42:50.222 --> 42:52.156
My sons don't have it easy
in school.

42:52.989 --> 42:55.121
Their teachers ain't even
teachin' them half the time.

42:55.123 --> 42:57.155
And you want to throw them
together with a bunch of nigras?

42:57.522 --> 42:59.622
It's only gonna get worse
for them.

43:00.689 --> 43:03.323
You ask why?
I'm here to protect my boys.

43:04.423 --> 43:06.789
So all the better
if she don't get in my way.

43:12.356 --> 43:13.923
I'll sit with you,
Brother Ellis.

43:19.823 --> 43:23.355
Howard, have you lost
your everlasting mind,

43:23.357 --> 43:25.022
callin' that man
your brother?

43:25.024 --> 43:26.788
You're offering
to co-chair, Howard?

43:26.790 --> 43:28.422
Uh, I am.

43:28.424 --> 43:30.588
And that's an honest man
right there, Ann.

43:30.590 --> 43:33.224
The only honest man
that's stood up today.

43:33.991 --> 43:36.763
He hates me.
And he told me why.

43:36.765 --> 43:40.732
But then he opened up
his heart about his sons.

43:41.131 --> 43:43.364
Why is he agreeing with me?

43:43.366 --> 43:45.564
- I don't know.
- That means he's my brother.

43:45.566 --> 43:47.132
Did that nigger
just call me brother?

43:49.967 --> 43:51.232
Y'all hear that?

43:52.466 --> 43:55.067
I'll tell you what you are,
Howard.

43:55.866 --> 43:57.900
You one of them
"big niggers," ain't you?

43:58.733 --> 44:01.998
You done went up north
and got your college degree,

44:02.000 --> 44:05.467
your fancy cars,
and your fancy suits.

44:06.099 --> 44:08.365
Meanwhile, we down here on
the ground gettin' dirty.

44:08.367 --> 44:10.731
Now wait a minute, Ann.

44:10.733 --> 44:13.565
The Black Solidarity Committee has
been working within this community...

44:13.567 --> 44:15.933
Oh, shut up, Howard!
You're late to the fight!

44:17.334 --> 44:21.300
And you have no idea what
real black folk go through.

44:21.800 --> 44:25.267
You don't deserve a seat.
He don't deserve that chair, he don't.

44:25.801 --> 44:27.734
Callin' that man his brother.

44:30.567 --> 44:32.767
So are you saying you'll accept
now, Miss Atwater?

45:19.269 --> 45:22.367
I'm going to continue to fight
for us white working men

45:22.369 --> 45:25.436
even if I have to sit in a room with
that awful Ann Atwater to do it.

45:27.402 --> 45:29.500
C.P. Ellis don't scare me.

45:29.502 --> 45:32.500
We gonna beat school
segregation once and for all.

45:32.502 --> 45:34.934
Well, she's livin'
in her own fantasy world.

45:34.936 --> 45:37.235
Folks in this town
like things the way they are.

46:50.205 --> 46:51.736
Good morning, Mr. Ellis.

46:51.738 --> 46:53.937
Co-chair office is
just around the corner.

46:53.939 --> 46:55.073
Thank you.

47:17.505 --> 47:21.104
All I'm saying is
our children are way behind.

47:21.106 --> 47:22.804
Almost a full year.

47:22.806 --> 47:24.938
Well,
just havin' white teachers

47:24.940 --> 47:26.840
isn't gonna help them
catch up.

47:28.206 --> 47:29.738
White teachers?

47:29.740 --> 47:31.438
They already got
some white teachers.

47:31.440 --> 47:33.605
It ain't that.
It's about the books.

47:33.607 --> 47:36.271
Newer books don't account
for a whole year.

47:36.273 --> 47:38.540
Newer ain't got
nothing to do with it.

47:39.239 --> 47:42.005
Baby, what's your name?
In the red shirt. What's your name?

47:42.007 --> 47:43.540
- Miles.
- Miles.

47:44.274 --> 47:46.438
What year did you
just finish, Miles?

47:46.440 --> 47:48.072
My junior year.
Mm-hmm.

47:48.074 --> 47:50.174
And what year
were your books for?

47:51.540 --> 47:53.274
The textbooks were
for the tenth-graders, ma'am.

47:58.107 --> 47:59.739
Well, how's that gonna work?

47:59.741 --> 48:01.872
How's what gonna work, C.P.?

48:01.874 --> 48:04.774
You gonna put a bunch of black
kids who are a year behind...

48:05.641 --> 48:07.073
with white kids who aren't.

48:07.075 --> 48:08.939
How you gonna teach
that class?

48:08.941 --> 48:11.305
You can't.
It just ain't possible.

48:11.307 --> 48:14.172
So you go ahead
and get the right books,

48:14.174 --> 48:17.708
but you can't teach
that class, no way. No way.

48:47.067 --> 48:48.731
Okay. So tomorrow,

48:48.733 --> 48:50.831
we'll break into
our smaller groups

48:50.833 --> 48:53.065
and begin hammering out the
different resolution points.

48:53.067 --> 48:56.098
But we meet back here
each night for wrap-up.

48:56.100 --> 48:59.366
Also, you've noticed these, uh,
two tables up here on the stage.

48:59.368 --> 49:02.731
Along with Mr. Ellis
and Miss Atwater,

49:02.733 --> 49:06.068
ten more of you will be chosen to fill
these seats as part of our senate.

49:06.434 --> 49:08.832
That senate will vote
on the resolutions

49:08.834 --> 49:10.534
on the final night
of the charrette.

49:11.701 --> 49:13.899
Okay.
Unless there's anything else,

49:13.901 --> 49:15.568
I think we could all use
some sleep.

49:16.402 --> 49:17.566
Yes, Reverend?

49:17.568 --> 49:19.266
Mr. Riddick,

49:19.268 --> 49:21.135
it's been
quite a tense day.

49:21.868 --> 49:27.566
It may be wise if we have some
positive note to end each session.

49:27.568 --> 49:29.533
Something to lift our spirits.

49:29.535 --> 49:31.633
I think that's a good idea,
Reverend.

49:31.635 --> 49:32.935
What did you have in mind?

49:33.303 --> 49:35.732
Well, I notice
we have a piano over here.

49:35.734 --> 49:39.000
What if we all sing gospel
music at the end of each night?

49:39.002 --> 49:40.735
- Okay.
- Nigger music.

49:41.702 --> 49:44.000
What did you say?

49:44.002 --> 49:46.700
I believe he said
that's nigger music.

49:46.702 --> 49:49.667
Gospel music don't have nothing
to do with black or white.

49:49.669 --> 49:52.900
It's about God.
Praise God, but he... he's right.

49:52.902 --> 49:55.767
Gospel music is absolutely
for black folk.

49:55.769 --> 49:58.134
I'm a bit surprised that
the reverend would suggest

49:58.136 --> 49:59.268
something so one-sided.

49:59.270 --> 50:00.867
I'm a little disappointed.

50:00.869 --> 50:02.436
Okay.
I can appreciate that, C.P.

50:02.802 --> 50:04.900
These people would like
gospel music.

50:04.902 --> 50:07.337
So, uh, how would you like
to represent your people?

50:09.735 --> 50:13.270
Well, I'd like to display our Klan
materials here at the charrette.

50:17.404 --> 50:18.537
Klan materials?

50:19.203 --> 50:20.437
Mm-hmm.

50:22.836 --> 50:25.502
It's not the same thing.
I know that.

50:25.504 --> 50:27.801
We can't let him do it. That stuff's
full of hate. That's all it is.

50:27.803 --> 50:30.202
He gave on the gospel.
I don't give a damn what he gave on.

50:30.204 --> 50:32.269
Well, he gave, so we give.

50:32.271 --> 50:35.202
Bill Riddick, if that stuff shows up
here, it's gonna be a riot.

50:35.204 --> 50:37.768
And you can bet your ass I'm gonna
be the one leading the charge.

50:37.770 --> 50:40.171
Oh, you gonna get all
Roughhouse Annie on me now, huh?

50:40.670 --> 50:43.871
Yeah, I heard tell about you.
All talkin' and no listenin'.

50:44.537 --> 50:47.735
We're here trying to understand each
other for once and stop fighting.

50:47.737 --> 50:50.403
I'll stop fightin' when there
ain't nothing left to fight for.

50:50.405 --> 50:52.804
Then you gonna be goin' uphill
the rest of your life, Ann.

50:53.837 --> 50:56.602
In the meantime,
I'm-a keep that man here talkin'

50:56.604 --> 50:58.339
as long as I possibly can.

51:00.804 --> 51:02.771
C.P.

51:04.072 --> 51:05.105
C.P.

51:07.637 --> 51:10.203
This, um,
display you want to bring.

51:10.205 --> 51:12.170
We're willing to go along
with it.

51:12.172 --> 51:13.903
But there'll be folks not wild
about the sight of it.

51:13.905 --> 51:16.103
So, uh, you're gonna need
to provide some security,

51:16.105 --> 51:18.037
someone to watch over it.

51:18.039 --> 51:19.539
I'm not gonna be responsible for it.

51:22.407 --> 51:23.872
This is my security.

51:24.705 --> 51:26.307
That gun
don't belong here.

51:27.005 --> 51:30.772
I like to have it close in case I
need it to do my talkin' for me.

51:32.106 --> 51:34.240
This here does the talkin'
for me.

51:34.472 --> 51:38.071
I have a Bible. Oh, you do?
Have you read it?

51:38.073 --> 51:39.439
Course I've read it.

51:39.906 --> 51:42.271
- Even go to church on Sundays.
- Hmm.

51:42.273 --> 51:44.338
Well, then,
you ought to know, C.P.

51:44.340 --> 51:45.373
Know what?

51:46.273 --> 51:48.906
Same God made you, made me.

52:10.639 --> 52:12.072
That's everything,
Mr. Ellis.

52:12.074 --> 52:13.874
Looks good, Ben. Real good.

52:14.174 --> 52:15.774
Thank you, Mr. Ellis.

52:26.874 --> 52:29.074
Divided according to race.

52:30.275 --> 52:32.507
Uh, six black, six white.

52:32.874 --> 52:35.705
The senate members will float in
and out of different working groups,

52:35.707 --> 52:37.540
observing and participating.

52:38.108 --> 52:40.040
On the final night
of the charrette,

52:40.042 --> 52:42.206
you will vote
to either adopt or reject

52:42.208 --> 52:43.873
the resolutions
presented to you.

52:43.875 --> 52:45.607
So, we're the final word?

52:45.875 --> 52:47.439
Final word, Howard.

52:47.441 --> 52:49.741
Two-thirds majority
to pass each resolution.

52:51.508 --> 52:52.942
Eight votes to pass?

52:54.075 --> 52:56.839
Then we should be able to handpick
the other four white members.

52:56.841 --> 52:59.006
Well, then, we might as well
go on home then.

52:59.008 --> 53:00.639
C.P.,
that's not practical.

53:00.641 --> 53:02.075
We need to be
as fair as possible.

53:02.376 --> 53:04.973
I'm gonna have to side
with my friend here.

53:04.975 --> 53:07.408
I mean,
we can surely all agree

53:07.410 --> 53:09.374
that every Negro
in the building

53:09.376 --> 53:11.241
is gonna vote yes
on school integration.

53:11.243 --> 53:13.374
That's six automatic votes,
no matter what.

53:13.376 --> 53:15.374
Same's not true
for every last white person.

53:15.376 --> 53:17.541
There's a bunch of liberals
sittin' out there right now.

53:19.509 --> 53:23.409
Look, there are four prominent
organizations represented

53:23.411 --> 53:25.207
in this room, right here.

53:25.209 --> 53:27.674
The Klan,
The White Citizens' Council,

53:27.676 --> 53:30.076
Black Solidarity Committee,
and Operation Breakthrough.

53:30.842 --> 53:32.144
You each get your votes.

53:32.575 --> 53:33.742
You want fair?

53:34.110 --> 53:36.010
We'll pick
eight regular members.

53:36.410 --> 53:39.809
Regular. No black power people, no Klan.
They're excluded.

53:41.194 --> 53:42.227
Agreed?

53:46.527 --> 53:48.358
- None of her people?
- No.

53:48.360 --> 53:49.860
And none of y'all.

54:06.127 --> 54:07.160
Hey!

54:07.793 --> 54:10.027
What do you think
you doing, huh?

54:12.295 --> 54:14.159
Leave that alone.

54:14.161 --> 54:16.693
Boys need to be reading this
instead of ripping it up.

54:17.495 --> 54:22.161
The Klan is givin' you
a window to look through.

54:24.595 --> 54:26.626
You need to read this stuff
and understand it.

54:26.628 --> 54:28.094
That way,
you understand them.

54:28.428 --> 54:31.959
Okay? You got the upper hand.
Got it?

54:31.961 --> 54:34.329
Get on outta here, Charles.
Give me that.

54:35.128 --> 54:37.329
Should tell your daddy.
You know better.

54:45.529 --> 54:47.262
Kids don't make no sense...

55:18.463 --> 55:22.428
"...professional experts from in
the community and from outside

55:22.430 --> 55:25.197
will stand by
listening, learning."

55:52.264 --> 55:53.929
Ann? Ann?
What?

55:53.931 --> 55:55.964
Where are you going?
I'm going home.

55:56.764 --> 55:58.496
Look,
I know you're upset, Ann.

55:58.498 --> 56:00.029
You don't know nothing!

56:00.031 --> 56:01.629
I told you
it was a damn fool idea

56:01.631 --> 56:03.596
to let that man
bring that stuff in here.

56:03.598 --> 56:05.365
Ain't no good
gonna come from it!

56:05.764 --> 56:08.031
And I'll tell you
something else, Bill Riddick.

56:08.631 --> 56:10.062
You an even bigger fool

56:10.064 --> 56:11.695
if you think you gonna make
any change

56:11.697 --> 56:13.163
with this here meeting.

56:13.165 --> 56:14.499
Is that right?
That's right.

56:15.065 --> 56:17.529
'Cause as long as
the C.P. Ellises of the world

56:17.531 --> 56:18.863
keep gettin' their way,

56:18.865 --> 56:20.363
ain't nothing gonna change.

56:20.365 --> 56:22.665
Yeah, you talk about
Roughhouse Annie?

56:23.631 --> 56:26.463
Keep Uncle Tommin'
that cracker

56:26.465 --> 56:28.632
and you gonna see
Roughhouse Annie.

56:29.698 --> 56:32.698
Go on back up north where you belong,
'cause you don't know nothing.

57:05.999 --> 57:07.200
Marion Wilson.

57:14.899 --> 57:17.034
Okay. The other bowl now.

57:20.067 --> 57:21.100
<i>Sam Watford.</i>

57:22.800 --> 57:24.700
- Is that Scooter Watford's boy?
- Yeah.

57:26.201 --> 57:27.800
You won't have
a problem there.

57:28.533 --> 57:30.134
You sure?
Pretty sure.

57:30.501 --> 57:33.265
I remember he kept losin' jobs
during them boycotts.

57:33.267 --> 57:34.634
Still pretty sore about it.

57:35.668 --> 57:37.967
I don't like that mustache,
tell you what.

57:38.335 --> 57:40.268
All right. Earl Weeks.

57:42.335 --> 57:43.700
He's... He's with us.

57:43.967 --> 57:45.235
How do you know?

57:46.035 --> 57:48.168
He been a deacon at my church
since I was a kid.

57:48.668 --> 57:49.935
He don't like nobody.

57:51.402 --> 57:54.666
- That's a good man.
- Two for two.

57:54.668 --> 57:58.300
Okay, we gonna have an issue
with this gal Maddy Mays.

57:58.302 --> 57:59.966
The blonde over by the window.

57:59.968 --> 58:01.333
Yeah, she's a nurse.

58:01.335 --> 58:02.834
Yeah, over at Durham Clinic.

58:03.302 --> 58:05.868
Real "people person." I think
that's one to worry about.

58:07.602 --> 58:09.099
Last is Lee Trombley.

58:09.101 --> 58:11.500
Trombley Hardware.

58:11.502 --> 58:12.602
Off of Route Nine.

58:13.535 --> 58:15.400
What do we know?

58:15.402 --> 58:17.002
I don't know 'bout him, C.P.

58:17.969 --> 58:19.069
<i>Might be a problem there.</i>

58:20.002 --> 58:22.069
<i>He took over
after his daddy passed.</i>

58:22.969 --> 58:25.402
<i>Family man, two kids, I think.</i>

58:25.735 --> 58:27.002
<i>And?</i>

58:27.869 --> 58:30.100
<i>Everybody that
works for him is a nigger.</i>

58:30.102 --> 58:31.136
<i>Every one.</i>

58:31.636 --> 58:33.670
And they all thick as thieves.

58:37.936 --> 58:41.204
All right, I guess it's time we
get acquainted with Lee Trombley.

59:02.937 --> 59:04.037
Can I help you, sir?

59:05.103 --> 59:07.370
Uh... Lee around?

59:07.703 --> 59:10.368
No, sir. He's not here right now.
But I'm the manager.

59:10.370 --> 59:11.671
Something I can help you with?

59:14.305 --> 59:15.671
Uh, no. Um...

59:16.504 --> 59:18.104
I'll come back another time.

59:29.572 --> 59:30.638
Okay.

59:31.138 --> 59:33.837
Any thoughts, uh, insights?

59:34.804 --> 59:36.505
You don't have to
raise your hand, Maddy.

59:36.804 --> 59:39.205
I think it's nice to see
people talking for once.

59:39.638 --> 59:41.505
That ain't talkin'.
It's yellin'.

59:41.871 --> 59:43.769
Well, okay. It's arguing.

59:43.771 --> 59:47.070
But people are listening to one another.
They really are.

59:47.072 --> 59:50.835
They're arguing.
I've been listening to it for days,

59:50.837 --> 59:53.870
and still no one's answered how
integration's gonna help my kids.

59:53.872 --> 59:57.037
- It sure can't hurt 'em.
- It sure as hell can.

59:57.039 --> 01:00:00.037
- I'd like to know how.
- Well, for one,

01:00:00.039 --> 01:00:03.005
I don't want my daughter sitting
next to a Negro boy in class.

01:00:03.438 --> 01:00:05.170
I don't want her
eatin' next to one,

01:00:05.172 --> 01:00:07.337
and don't want her being
at a school dance with one.

01:00:07.339 --> 01:00:09.673
So, you care
about your daughter?

01:00:10.805 --> 01:00:12.703
And you don't want
to see her get hurt.

01:00:12.705 --> 01:00:14.370
What's your point?

01:00:14.372 --> 01:00:18.339
My point is that is
what we do as parents.

01:00:19.339 --> 01:00:23.238
When they're little, we try to
keep them from touching the stove

01:00:23.240 --> 01:00:24.439
so they don't burn.

01:00:25.372 --> 01:00:28.606
We teach them to take small
bites so they don't choke.

01:00:29.406 --> 01:00:32.038
We worry about
their first day at school,

01:00:32.040 --> 01:00:33.538
the first time
they drive a car,

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:35.304
their very first job.

01:00:35.306 --> 01:00:40.104
See, we want them to avoid
the pain that we experienced.

01:00:40.106 --> 01:00:42.073
All right. All right.

01:00:42.373 --> 01:00:44.971
We all gonna sit around,
hold hands, sing "Kumbaya"?

01:00:44.973 --> 01:00:47.871
- We see what you're doing, Howard.
- And what is that, C.P.?

01:00:47.873 --> 01:00:50.206
That there's no difference
between blacks and whites, right?

01:00:50.208 --> 01:00:52.838
'Cause we all worry
about our kids.

01:00:52.840 --> 01:00:54.672
We're all the same, right?

01:00:54.674 --> 01:00:59.572
Actually, no, C.P. We're not.

01:00:59.574 --> 01:01:01.440
See, I left some things out.

01:01:02.174 --> 01:01:04.705
I left out
that black folks have

01:01:04.707 --> 01:01:07.707
a whole different menu of pain
to worry about.

01:01:08.840 --> 01:01:11.675
Our kids get spit on
for no reason.

01:01:12.508 --> 01:01:17.374
Our kids have to move on the
sidewalk to let white folks pass,

01:01:18.008 --> 01:01:19.341
or they get beat.

01:01:20.408 --> 01:01:22.774
Our kids aren't allowed
to sit where they want,

01:01:23.208 --> 01:01:26.675
play where they want,
go to school where they want.

01:01:27.808 --> 01:01:32.173
See, this is the pain
they experience every day

01:01:32.175 --> 01:01:35.741
that we, we can't...
can't spare them from.

01:01:37.442 --> 01:01:40.142
And that is a...

01:01:42.375 --> 01:01:43.875
It's a helpless feeling.

01:01:45.475 --> 01:01:48.509
A more helpless feeling
than you could ever know.

01:01:57.976 --> 01:02:00.307
I fell right into that one.
Yeah.

01:02:00.309 --> 01:02:02.909
Shit. You see Trombley's face?
Yeah.

01:02:03.643 --> 01:02:06.840
Did you get anywhere with Trombley
last night? He wasn't there.

01:02:06.842 --> 01:02:09.175
They were right, though.
He got a black manager.

01:02:09.842 --> 01:02:11.709
Well, where we gonna
get him, then?

01:02:12.143 --> 01:02:14.274
Right now.
We gonna crowd him at lunch.

01:02:14.276 --> 01:02:15.707
Mmm.

01:02:15.709 --> 01:02:17.677
Okay.
Everybody listen up.

01:02:18.842 --> 01:02:20.709
We're going to be trying
something different today.

01:02:21.110 --> 01:02:24.077
There are name cards at
each seat in this lunchroom.

01:02:24.476 --> 01:02:27.141
This will be your seat
for the rest of the charrette.

01:02:27.143 --> 01:02:29.210
You may not move
your name card.

01:02:30.210 --> 01:02:32.708
And you guessed it,
the person sitting next to you

01:02:32.710 --> 01:02:34.408
will not be
the same color as you.

01:02:34.410 --> 01:02:36.141
- What?
- And...

01:02:36.143 --> 01:02:39.975
And no discussion of issues
during this hour.

01:02:39.977 --> 01:02:41.210
Talk about something else.

01:04:07.547 --> 01:04:09.077
I just can't do it. Mm-mm.

01:04:09.079 --> 01:04:11.647
Mm-mm! Mm-mm-mm.

01:04:12.846 --> 01:04:14.913
These fish sticks is dry.

01:04:21.447 --> 01:04:22.914
Well... Hmm.

01:04:23.647 --> 01:04:25.581
If we can't change
anything else,

01:04:25.981 --> 01:04:28.447
we can sure demand
better school lunches, huh?

01:04:29.013 --> 01:04:30.914
We're not supposed to
talk about issues.

01:04:32.881 --> 01:04:34.280
I guess you're right.

01:04:41.013 --> 01:04:42.047
Howard...

01:04:42.847 --> 01:04:44.847
Howard was wrong in there,
weren't he?

01:04:45.548 --> 01:04:47.381
Wrong?
Mm-hmm.

01:04:49.048 --> 01:04:53.712
Well, I mean, he weren't wrong
about what black kids go through.

01:04:53.714 --> 01:04:54.747
But...

01:04:56.215 --> 01:05:01.081
He was wrong about you not knowing
what helpless is, weren't he?

01:05:04.549 --> 01:05:05.748
What does that mean?

01:05:09.915 --> 01:05:12.248
You got a boy out at Murdock,
don't you, C.P.?

01:05:12.683 --> 01:05:14.681
- I don't wanna talk about that.
- I'm just trying...

01:05:14.683 --> 01:05:17.349
Ann, don't talk about my son.

01:05:18.981 --> 01:05:21.216
Don't ever talk about my son.
Okay.

01:05:48.317 --> 01:05:50.648
We're willing to go
to summer school,

01:05:50.650 --> 01:05:52.881
even nights, just to catch
up with the white students.

01:05:52.883 --> 01:05:56.016
Good Lord never intended for
blacks to have equal rights.

01:07:11.653 --> 01:07:14.418
Daddy! What's wrong?
What's wrong, sugar?

01:07:14.420 --> 01:07:15.453
It's Larry.

01:07:26.486 --> 01:07:29.284
What's goin' on?

01:07:29.286 --> 01:07:31.850
- Who is this?
- Alvin. He moved in Friday.

01:07:31.852 --> 01:07:34.520
Hey, hey.
Shh, shh. Shh, shh, shh.

01:07:36.819 --> 01:07:39.053
Hey, pumpkin.

01:07:40.220 --> 01:07:42.051
- Go! It's okay.
- It's okay.

01:07:42.053 --> 01:07:44.419
No monster.
No monster, son. No monster.

01:07:44.421 --> 01:07:46.051
I got your book.
I'm gonna read...

01:07:46.053 --> 01:07:47.718
Shh, shh, shh.
Shh, shh, shh.

01:07:47.720 --> 01:07:48.852
It's Vickie.

01:07:49.154 --> 01:07:50.850
Read to him.
Okay.

01:07:50.852 --> 01:07:53.285
Come here, pumpkin.
I'll be right back.

01:07:53.287 --> 01:07:55.987
- Vickie's gonna read to you.
- It's your sister, Vickie.

01:07:56.554 --> 01:07:57.753
Get him out.

01:08:01.454 --> 01:08:04.319
Hey, who's in charge here?
Can I help you, Mr. Ellis?

01:08:04.321 --> 01:08:06.485
No. Is there someone else
I can talk to?

01:08:06.487 --> 01:08:07.719
One moment.

01:08:07.721 --> 01:08:08.754
Hey.

01:08:12.589 --> 01:08:14.219
Hey.

01:08:14.221 --> 01:08:15.520
I'll be right there.
I need help.

01:08:15.522 --> 01:08:17.152
No, sir. No, sir.
I need help.

01:08:17.154 --> 01:08:18.818
My son needs help.
Step outside that door.

01:08:18.819 --> 01:08:20.687
I need to get my son out of that room.
Yes, sir.

01:08:20.689 --> 01:08:22.818
Step outside for a moment.

01:08:22.819 --> 01:08:25.153
Now calm it down.
I need to get my son out of that room.

01:08:25.154 --> 01:08:27.319
Your son is gonna be just fine.
He's scared.

01:08:27.322 --> 01:08:28.821
He's not fine.
He needs to be moved.

01:08:29.055 --> 01:08:30.986
Right away.
Or that other one needs to be moved.

01:08:30.988 --> 01:08:33.286
My son's scared.
Look. Look.

01:08:33.287 --> 01:08:35.919
It's important that our patients
stay in familiar surroundings.

01:08:35.921 --> 01:08:38.819
'Cause if they're moved
too often, they get agitated...

01:08:38.821 --> 01:08:40.587
A private room then.

01:08:40.590 --> 01:08:42.354
Give Larry a private room,
please.

01:08:42.356 --> 01:08:43.919
We have regulations
here at Murdock.

01:08:43.921 --> 01:08:46.185
I don't care
about your regulations.

01:08:46.188 --> 01:08:49.421
Now you move him, or I will.
How's that? No, you will not.

01:08:49.423 --> 01:08:53.421
Mr. Ellis!
Call security right now.

01:08:53.423 --> 01:08:55.523
You calm yourself down.

01:08:59.754 --> 01:09:00.755
God...

01:09:01.555 --> 01:09:03.389
How much...
How much is it again?

01:09:03.755 --> 01:09:07.853
A private room is $75 more
per week.

01:09:07.854 --> 01:09:09.557
Now do you wanna pay for that?

01:09:10.854 --> 01:09:12.321
I got 16.

01:09:12.323 --> 01:09:14.390
Mr. Ellis.
Listen to me.

01:09:15.055 --> 01:09:18.156
Larry will get used to it,
all right?

01:09:22.956 --> 01:09:26.354
You shoulda told me. No one told
me that boy would be in this room.

01:09:26.357 --> 01:09:27.622
It was...
No one told me.

01:09:27.624 --> 01:09:29.154
It was a last minute...

01:09:29.157 --> 01:09:30.357
You shoulda told me.

01:10:10.058 --> 01:10:11.989
You know,
I'm tryin' to tell you now.

01:10:11.991 --> 01:10:14.524
His roommate was wailin'
and screamin' and...

01:10:14.526 --> 01:10:16.158
But they wouldn't
let me move him.

01:10:19.326 --> 01:10:20.757
I wanna take him home.

01:10:22.492 --> 01:10:24.059
He's better off with us.

01:10:26.559 --> 01:10:28.192
He don't belong there.

01:10:28.559 --> 01:10:30.025
He ain't like them others.

01:10:31.825 --> 01:10:33.992
<i>Yes, Claiborne, he is.</i>

01:10:37.560 --> 01:10:40.292
<i>I'm seeing him tomorrow.
I'm sure he's fine.</i>

01:10:41.725 --> 01:10:42.890
<i>You okay?</i>

01:10:42.892 --> 01:10:44.393
Yeah, I'm just tired.

01:10:46.594 --> 01:10:48.527
I'll see you at home.
I love you.

01:13:55.773 --> 01:13:57.005
Can I help you?

01:13:57.606 --> 01:13:59.606
You can't,
but Bernadette can.

01:14:00.939 --> 01:14:02.606
One moment.
Thank you.

01:14:08.440 --> 01:14:10.937
Miss Atwater!

01:14:10.939 --> 01:14:15.772
Oh, my gosh. Oh, my gosh.
How have you been?

01:14:15.774 --> 01:14:18.738
Oh, baby, I've been good.
How about yourself?

01:14:18.740 --> 01:14:20.904
I'm fine. I'm just fine.

01:14:20.906 --> 01:14:22.674
Well,
what can I help you with?

01:14:24.774 --> 01:14:26.774
Where's that Larry Ellis boy?

01:14:37.807 --> 01:14:38.840
Bernadette.

01:14:39.507 --> 01:14:42.374
Yes, Miss Atwater?
I'm gonna need a favor.

01:14:43.807 --> 01:14:46.272
But that's not fair.
I know it's not fair, honey.

01:14:46.274 --> 01:14:48.373
But I went back and looked.
Not even half of them are done yet.

01:14:48.375 --> 01:14:50.005
But she never does
any of her charts.

01:14:50.007 --> 01:14:52.072
She always expects us
to do them for her.

01:14:52.074 --> 01:14:54.775
You and I have to go over all her
work, or it's gonna be on us.

01:15:04.075 --> 01:15:05.108
Hello?

01:15:06.941 --> 01:15:07.975
Hello?

01:15:08.375 --> 01:15:10.373
Where's Larry? Where's my son?

01:15:10.375 --> 01:15:11.575
He's not in his room.
What happened?

01:15:11.808 --> 01:15:13.676
Nothing happened, Miss Ellis.

01:15:14.108 --> 01:15:15.442
He was moved.

01:15:22.841 --> 01:15:24.008
It's so nice.

01:15:27.642 --> 01:15:28.676
Hey, baby.

01:15:29.343 --> 01:15:30.642
It's your mama.

01:15:32.475 --> 01:15:34.009
Hey, baby, it's your mama.

01:15:34.276 --> 01:15:35.809
- Hi.
- Hi.

01:15:37.143 --> 01:15:38.676
Let's put on some music.

01:15:51.876 --> 01:15:52.909
What?

01:15:54.809 --> 01:15:57.277
No, no, it's good. It's...

01:15:59.244 --> 01:16:00.576
It's just, uh...

01:16:04.110 --> 01:16:05.677
All right,
I'll see you at home.

01:16:18.477 --> 01:16:21.144
I want to talk to you.
Finally.

01:16:21.778 --> 01:16:23.177
Look. What you, uh...

01:16:24.810 --> 01:16:27.178
I didn't... I...

01:16:30.378 --> 01:16:32.276
I didn't ask for your help.

01:16:32.278 --> 01:16:34.475
I can take care of
my own family, okay?

01:16:34.477 --> 01:16:36.076
Okay.
Okay.

01:16:36.078 --> 01:16:37.976
Okay.
It's just what I do, C.P.

01:16:37.978 --> 01:16:41.076
Well, whatever is you do,
don't do it for me.

01:16:41.078 --> 01:16:42.444
I didn't do it for you.

01:16:54.712 --> 01:16:57.110
- Strike one!
- Yeah, Chester, bring the heat!

01:16:57.112 --> 01:16:59.246
All right, shut your hole.
That ain't helping.

01:17:01.978 --> 01:17:06.012
Don't pay him no mind, boy.
He ain't goin' nowhere with two outs.

01:17:07.079 --> 01:17:08.678
They'll hold 'em.
Be all right.

01:17:22.380 --> 01:17:23.414
I'll be right back.

01:17:31.746 --> 01:17:33.414
Your boy playing today?
Oh.

01:17:34.213 --> 01:17:35.280
Mr. Ellis.

01:17:36.013 --> 01:17:38.213
Uh, no. My nephew.

01:17:38.613 --> 01:17:40.444
You can call me C.P.
You want a beer?

01:17:40.446 --> 01:17:41.677
Oh. Thanks.

01:17:41.679 --> 01:17:42.946
Strike!

01:17:45.579 --> 01:17:47.814
So, how do you think
it's going? The charrette.

01:17:49.247 --> 01:17:50.580
Um...

01:17:51.280 --> 01:17:52.280
It's interesting.

01:17:53.547 --> 01:17:55.414
It's nice to hear
both sides, you know.

01:17:55.714 --> 01:17:57.213
Yeah. Yeah.

01:17:59.013 --> 01:18:00.881
We got some decisions to make.

01:18:01.714 --> 01:18:03.181
Strike three! You're out!

01:18:05.913 --> 01:18:08.181
Say, that nigger fella?
The one that comes, uh...

01:18:10.714 --> 01:18:12.281
He runs your hardware store?

01:18:12.647 --> 01:18:14.848
Yeah. 'Bout two years now.

01:18:15.214 --> 01:18:16.314
His name's Emmett.

01:18:17.248 --> 01:18:20.047
And you trust him to...
to run things?

01:18:23.648 --> 01:18:25.746
Sorry, I-I'm just curious.

01:18:25.748 --> 01:18:29.615
I don't think I could trust one
of them to run my filling station.

01:18:30.415 --> 01:18:32.914
Other than my wife,
he's the only person I trust.

01:18:33.581 --> 01:18:34.713
How's that?

01:18:34.715 --> 01:18:36.748
Well, he and I, we...

01:18:39.015 --> 01:18:40.615
We were in Vietnam together.

01:18:42.415 --> 01:18:44.716
Oh. You were in Vietnam?
Yeah.

01:18:45.082 --> 01:18:47.548
Two tours. Got out in '68.

01:18:48.048 --> 01:18:49.115
You?

01:18:49.716 --> 01:18:51.315
No. No, I...

01:18:53.716 --> 01:18:54.816
No.

01:18:56.849 --> 01:18:57.915
Yeah.

01:18:58.883 --> 01:19:01.046
Well, look, Mr. Ellis,
I know who you are.

01:19:01.048 --> 01:19:02.547
And I know
what you want from me.

01:19:02.549 --> 01:19:04.480
But I just don't...
No, no, Lee.

01:19:04.482 --> 01:19:06.480
Any man who served bravely
in this country's military

01:19:06.482 --> 01:19:08.549
doesn't need to hear
anything more from me.

01:19:09.250 --> 01:19:10.783
You vote how you want to.

01:19:11.549 --> 01:19:12.616
I'll respect it.

01:19:16.183 --> 01:19:17.216
Mr. Ellis?

01:19:19.183 --> 01:19:20.850
Emmett served
this country, too.

01:19:22.483 --> 01:19:24.784
And he was a lot braver
than me.

01:19:40.050 --> 01:19:42.615
All right, folks.
For our last day,

01:19:42.617 --> 01:19:44.282
I thought we'd go
on a little field trip.

01:19:44.284 --> 01:19:46.849
Where to?
You gotta vote Monday night.

01:19:46.851 --> 01:19:49.215
I think it's important
we get a firsthand look

01:19:49.217 --> 01:19:51.050
at what we've been talkin'
about the past few weeks.

01:20:14.852 --> 01:20:17.384
I know it's been a long
day, but this is the last one.

01:20:18.685 --> 01:20:20.752
Please be careful.
Watch your step.

01:20:21.152 --> 01:20:24.652
Ain't no better over here.
It's a mess.

01:20:25.051 --> 01:20:27.550
They gotta keep the doors open
because of the smell.

01:20:27.552 --> 01:20:29.419
I imagine so.
It helps.

01:20:34.052 --> 01:20:35.884
Lot of kids
for summer school.

01:20:35.886 --> 01:20:38.252
Uh...
That ain't summer school, C.P.

01:20:39.019 --> 01:20:41.250
They still tryin' to finish up
from last year.

01:20:41.252 --> 01:20:44.084
Yes, because of the split
shifts after the fire,

01:20:44.086 --> 01:20:45.751
the students
were really only getting

01:20:45.753 --> 01:20:48.184
about three hours
of schooling per day.

01:20:48.186 --> 01:20:50.219
So, they're still catching up.

01:20:52.019 --> 01:20:54.418
Hey, how you doin'?
Did you get them shoes I sent you?

01:20:54.420 --> 01:20:55.885
Mama!

01:20:55.887 --> 01:20:58.119
Hey.
Oh, this your girl?

01:20:59.253 --> 01:21:00.486
Hey.
Hi.

01:21:01.353 --> 01:21:04.353
Marilynn,
this here is, uh, Mr. Ellis.

01:21:06.020 --> 01:21:07.187
Oh.

01:21:08.520 --> 01:21:10.286
Well, I better get to class.

01:21:10.987 --> 01:21:12.120
Okay.

01:21:20.353 --> 01:21:22.788
She looked at me like I was
some kind of monster.

01:21:24.087 --> 01:21:25.353
What'd you expect?

01:21:27.821 --> 01:21:29.752
I don't know.
I'm trying to do right by us.

01:21:29.754 --> 01:21:31.252
Make it all better.

01:21:31.254 --> 01:21:33.287
And how's this gonna
make it all better?

01:21:33.888 --> 01:21:35.719
Hell, I'm...

01:21:35.721 --> 01:21:37.886
They wanted to integrate restaurants.
So we did.

01:21:37.888 --> 01:21:40.452
Then came buses and bathrooms
and playgrounds.

01:21:40.454 --> 01:21:42.218
Look, I'm over there right now

01:21:42.220 --> 01:21:44.119
supporting more funding
to make their schools better.

01:21:44.121 --> 01:21:46.218
If they have nicer schools, they'll...

01:21:46.220 --> 01:21:48.052
...stop pushin'
to integrate ours.

01:21:48.054 --> 01:21:49.954
The one thing we have left.

01:21:50.254 --> 01:21:52.254
Then maybe
we'll all stop fighting.

01:21:52.588 --> 01:21:53.921
Then what you gonna do?

01:21:55.921 --> 01:21:56.954
What?

01:21:58.187 --> 01:22:00.221
When everybody stops fighting,
who you gonna fight?

01:23:12.590 --> 01:23:14.090
Okay. Coming.

01:23:20.257 --> 01:23:21.656
Can I help you?

01:23:21.658 --> 01:23:23.525
Hi, Ann. Um...

01:23:24.424 --> 01:23:26.257
I'm Mary Ellis.
Claiborne's wife.

01:23:28.758 --> 01:23:29.924
Oh.

01:23:30.425 --> 01:23:33.090
I'm sorry
for just dropping by. I, um...

01:23:34.258 --> 01:23:37.957
I wanted to thank you for, um,
what you did

01:23:38.458 --> 01:23:40.158
for our family,
for our son Larry.

01:23:42.425 --> 01:23:43.558
Please, come in.

01:23:47.358 --> 01:23:48.625
Thanks.
Go on in.

01:23:52.793 --> 01:23:55.592
Hope you like sweet tea.
I do.

01:23:58.392 --> 01:24:01.225
So Larry is doing better, huh?

01:24:01.893 --> 01:24:03.057
He is.

01:24:03.692 --> 01:24:05.592
You know,
sometimes it's hard to...

01:24:07.125 --> 01:24:09.459
keep him calm.
Mm.

01:24:12.058 --> 01:24:15.592
Well, has, uh...
has Larry always been like that?

01:24:16.092 --> 01:24:17.259
Yeah.

01:24:18.426 --> 01:24:20.760
You know, when he was little,
it just...

01:24:21.526 --> 01:24:23.527
He started not to be able
to do things.

01:24:28.693 --> 01:24:30.991
Has C.P. always been
like that?

01:24:30.993 --> 01:24:32.858
Oh.

01:24:32.860 --> 01:24:33.894
Yes.

01:24:35.660 --> 01:24:36.693
More or less.

01:24:39.026 --> 01:24:42.591
You know, he used to be
a really good baseball player.

01:24:42.593 --> 01:24:44.024
Really?
Showed a lot of promise.

01:24:44.026 --> 01:24:45.291
Colleges came
and looked at him

01:24:45.293 --> 01:24:47.627
right over here
at Liberty Park.

01:24:48.761 --> 01:24:50.258
Where we met, actually.

01:24:50.260 --> 01:24:52.160
Came up to me,
he's so nervous.

01:24:52.960 --> 01:24:55.326
Couldn't even talk.
So handsome.

01:24:55.960 --> 01:24:58.258
Oh.

01:24:58.260 --> 01:24:59.293
What?

01:24:59.927 --> 01:25:01.828
C.P. handsome?
Oh.

01:25:02.861 --> 01:25:03.960
He was.

01:25:07.060 --> 01:25:08.261
Okay.

01:25:09.861 --> 01:25:11.896
Mm-hmm.
Oh.

01:25:13.896 --> 01:25:14.928
Thank you again.

01:25:15.161 --> 01:25:16.194
You're welcome.

01:25:22.060 --> 01:25:24.727
Ann...
Yes?

01:25:24.729 --> 01:25:26.462
Claiborne is, uh...

01:25:29.595 --> 01:25:31.295
He's doing
the best he can.

01:25:34.395 --> 01:25:35.727
Bye.

01:25:35.729 --> 01:25:36.896
Good-bye, Miss Ellis.

01:25:58.396 --> 01:26:00.059
Gimme a minute with C.P.,
would you?

01:26:00.061 --> 01:26:01.296
Sure thing, Floyd.

01:26:19.864 --> 01:26:21.764
Hey. What do you say, Floyd?

01:26:24.363 --> 01:26:25.430
You got one of those?

01:26:33.664 --> 01:26:35.062
See the paper?

01:26:36.062 --> 01:26:39.097
Nothin' I could do about that.
All part of this charrette business.

01:26:44.097 --> 01:26:45.797
It don't look right.

01:26:45.799 --> 01:26:47.462
It don't matter
what it looks like, Floyd.

01:26:47.464 --> 01:26:48.763
Matters what it is.

01:26:48.765 --> 01:26:50.130
Oh, yeah.

01:26:50.732 --> 01:26:53.930
Your wife making friends
with Ann Atwater what it is?

01:26:55.364 --> 01:26:56.397
What?

01:26:57.963 --> 01:26:59.832
Couple of the boys
saw 'em today.

01:27:01.963 --> 01:27:03.565
How am I supposed to
explain that?

01:27:10.598 --> 01:27:12.430
She did something for Larry
is all.

01:27:12.432 --> 01:27:14.298
Mary was just
probably thanking her.

01:27:14.931 --> 01:27:17.029
Niggers is doing you
favors now, C.P.?

01:27:17.031 --> 01:27:18.698
Stop with the bullshit, Floyd.

01:27:19.098 --> 01:27:20.733
Mary's always gone
her own way.

01:27:21.398 --> 01:27:24.263
Has nothin' to do with how
I do my business. Never has.

01:27:24.265 --> 01:27:25.899
Now you got something to say?
Say it.

01:27:28.566 --> 01:27:30.131
Look around you, C.P.

01:27:30.533 --> 01:27:33.031
All these guys,
